1. Full Binary Tree: Every node in the tree must have either 0 or 2 child nodes. 




2. Complete Binary Tree: All the levels should be completely filled, except possibly the last level and all nodes in the last level must be as left as possible.




3. Balanced Binary Tree: The maximum depth of a node in the left subtree and that of right subtree must not differ by more than 1 for all the nodes in the tree. For e.g., the image shown in full binary tree is not balanced but the ones shown in complete binary tree is balanced.

4. Skewed Binary Tree: A skewed binary tree is a type of binary tree in which all the nodes have only either one child or no child.

